id="loop-meta"><h1 class="loop-meta-title">Tag Archives: <span>Renewable</span></h1><div
class="loop-meta-description"></div></div><div
id="post-4269" class="post-4269 post type-post status-publish format-standard hentry category-energy category-environment tag-dubai tag-kuwait tag-oman tag-renewable tag-saudi-arabia tag-solar tag-uae"><h2 class="entry-title"><a
href="http://www.thingsaregood.com/2014/02/06/solar-power-rising-in-the-gulf/" title="Permalink to Solar Power Rising in the Gulf" rel="bookmark">Solar Power Rising in the Gulf</a></h2><div
class="entry-meta"> <span
class="entry-date" title="2014/02/06 11:06 am"><a
href="http://www.thingsaregood.com/2014/02/06/solar-power-rising-in-the-gulf/" title="Solar Power Rising in the Gulf" rel="bookmark">2014/02/06 11:06 am</a></span><span
class="entry-meta-sep"> / </span><span
class="comments-link"><a
href="http://www.thingsaregood.com/2014/02/06/solar-power-rising-in-the-gulf/#comments">Leave a Comment</a></span><span
class="entry-meta-sep"> / </span><span
class="entry-author author vcard"><a
href="http://www.thingsaregood.com/author/administrator/" title="by Adam Clare" rel="author">Adam Clare</a></span></div><div
class="entry-content clearfix"><p>2013 saw great things happen on the Arabian Peninsula in relation to energy production. The region has invested heavily in installing solar power plants and reducing their own reliance on oil (so they can export more). In fact, the UAE is looking to start export in renewable energy!</p><blockquote><p>For the Gulf&#8217;s solar industry, 2013 was a year of firsts: In addition to the opening of Abu Dhabi&#8217;s Shams 1 plant, Dubai&#8217;s first solar power plant became operational, and Kuwait and Oman decided to build their first as well. In Saudi Arabia, one energy analyst found the cost of generating electricity from solar there had become as cheap as generating electricity from oil-fired power plants.</p><p>Saudi&#8217;s solar goals appear to be the most gung-ho in the region: The kingdom has announced that it plans to throw down $109bn on solar energy and get one-third of its power from the sun by 2032. This target is &#8220;too ambitious&#8221;, said Hussam Khonkar of Saudi Arabia&#8217;s King Abdulaziz City for Science and Technology, but added the technology to do so is available.</p></blockquote><p><a
href="http://www.aljazeera.com/indepth/features/2014/01/gulf-bright-solar-powered-future-201412363550740672.html">Read more.</a></p><div
class='sharedaddy sd-block sd-like jetpack-likes-widget-wrapper jetpack-likes-widget-unloaded' id='like-post-wrapper-1111807-4269-53836f8d5fcc6' data-src='//widgets.wp.com/likes/#blog_id=1111807&amp;post_id=4269&amp;origin=www.thingsaregood.com&amp;obj_id=1111807-4269-53836f8d5fcc6' data-name='like-post-frame-1111807-4269-53836f8d5fcc6'><h3 class='sd-title'>Like this:</h3><div
